The "culprit Putin"
Moscow — Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden have unanimously concluded that Alexei Navalny was a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is Russia's most prominent opponent of President Vladimir Putin and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Fund.
Fortunately, since Navalny survived, the relations between Russia and Germany did not deteriorate.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel stated that Navalny is "a victim of persecution due to freedom of speech."
In her eyes, the incident was very serious, and only the Russian government could, and must, respond.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation's findings prove that the Russian government is the mastermind behind the incident, the European Commission will impose a new round of sanctions.
Regardless, according to the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is prohibited.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to deal with its political rivals.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both of them survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny incident, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov firmly stated, "There is no evidence to accuse the Russian government."
Sergei Naryshkin, director of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, even claimed that this was the act of Western intelligence agencies, thereby damaging the credibility of the Russian government.
Narishkin's argument clearly lacks justification, but he also pointed out a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
It's indefensible to poison a prominent political rival just before an upcoming election, especially using a poison developed by the former Soviet Union.
This timing is even more intriguing, especially as the people of the neighboring country Belarus are protesting against the elections held in August.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was particularly confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more thoroughly before committing the crime?
If it really was the Russian government that did it, as Germany claims, this murder was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of international politics (the top rebel figure in the movie Star Wars), intervening in the US election, inciting street protests in France, enticing Brexit in the UK, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he was shrewd, visionary, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why could Navalny flee to Germany, and why was he quickly diagnosed with poisoning?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream gas pipeline to Germany is under threat of cancellation.
This murder was clearly not worth it.
In fact, this further fueled the public's opposition to the atrocities of the Russian authorities.
If it's not Putin who did it, then accusing Western intelligence agencies is even more unjustified.
If such allegations are true, German and Swedish scientists would not have disclosed the fact about the nerve agent Novichok.
More possibilities come from conspiracies orchestrated by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to shut up before the presidential election, or perhaps it was the trouble caused by his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy a variety of products and services on the black market, including military nerve agents.
Although Putin's political enforcers are loyal, they are also quite stupid; they thought it was a good idea to poison Navalny, and only a few participants knew the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts share similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Murza was the coordinator of the public investigation committee of Khodorkovsky.
Poisoning of Mediazona publisher Peter Verkholov in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on judicial abuse in Russia.
It can be traced back further to 2006, when Alexander Litvinenko was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko often criticized Russia's security agencies.
Just like the Navalny case, such poisoning often backfires.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a column writer for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan. Although she survived, she was later shot dead in the elevator of her apartment two years later.
As Putin said, her death has caused significant damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
Whether or not Putin personally directed it, the system he created made such crimes possible. Such a system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death was the desired outcome for the Kremlin, and pleasing Master Putin is the ultimate goal of the hounds.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning attempt fails, they will not be punished.
Because they did it for the president's benefit.
Those who hope to find proof of poisoning may be disappointed.
No matter what, the Kremlin is the real culprit.
Western countries must clearly state that they will impose sanctions on Russia even if their own economies are affected.
Putin created a system centered around himself.
All the responsibilities in Russia are attributed to himself.
